{"answerId":"ans-24a9cdd53311","mode":"rag","confidence":0.94,"answer":"Here is a simple NeTEx XML example for a line with stop points, based on the provided evidence:\n\n```xml\n<Network>\n    <StopPlace id=\"stop_place_1\">\n        <Name>Stop Place 1</Name>\n        <Location>\n            <Latitude>36.905697</Latitude>\n            <Longitude>-116.76218</Longitude>\n        </Location>\n    </StopPlace>\n    <ScheduledStopPoint id=\"scheduled_stop_point_1\">\n        <PublicCode>SSP_001</PublicCode>\n        <Name>Scheduled Stop Point 1</Name>\n        <Location>\n            <Latitude>36.905697</Latitude>\n            <Longitude>-116.76218</Longitude>\n        </Location>\n    </ScheduledStopPoint>\n    <StopAssignment>\n        <StopPlaceRef ref=\"stop_place_1\"/>\n        <ScheduledStopPointRef ref=\"scheduled_stop_point_1\"/>\n    </StopAssignment>\n</Network>\n```\n\nThis example illustrates the relationship between a `StopPlace` and a `ScheduledStopPoint`, as well as their association through a `StopAssignment`, which is consistent with the NeTEx structure described in the evidence [E1], [E6]. However, the evidence does not provide a complete XML structure for a full line with multiple stop points, so I cannot provide a more extensive example safely.","citations":[{"repositoryUrl":"https://github.com/NeTEx-CEN/NeTEx/blob/de021e83a02522cff4ed936408bf927f798aae0d/examples/functions/timetable/Netex_07.2_Bus_FlexibleTimetable_WithPattern.xml","commitSha":"de021e83a02522cff4ed936408bf927f798aae0d","sourcePath":"examples/functions/timetable/Netex_07.2_Bus_FlexibleTimetable_WithPattern.xml","chunkId":"src-13aed64e9579795bede68871","label":"examples/functions/timetable/Netex_07.2_Bus_FlexibleTimetable_WithPattern.xml"},{"repositoryUrl":"https://github.com/NeTEx-CEN/NeTEx/blob/de021e83a02522cff4ed936408bf927f798aae0d/examples/functions/timetable/Netex_08.1_BusTram_Timetable_AmbiguousLinks.xml","commitSha":"de021e83a02522cff4ed936408bf927f798aae0d","sourcePath":"exa